on_city":"Mendon","location_state":"Massachusetts","location_country":"United States"}],"tags":["minister","missionary","author","king_williams_war","harvard_graduate"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909"},{"short":"Rawson Family Memorial 1875"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["religion","literature"],"notable_blurb":"Mendon minister; Algonquian translator; Cotton Mather classmate","primary_url":"https://americanantiquarian.org/EnglishtoAlgonquian/grindalrawson","primary_url_label":"American Antiquarian Society"},"quotes":[{"text":"To my Beloved Wife Mrs Susanna Rawson who tho last in mention yet deserveth the first in my best and sincere affections","attribution":"Rev. Grindal Rawson, Will dated Jan 24, 1714","category":"family"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Named for Elizabeth I's Archbishop of Canterbury","body":"He was named \"Grindal\" after Edmund Grindal, Archbishop of Canterbury under Elizabeth I — his great-great-grandmother's brother, per the Harvard commencement of 1678. At that ceremony President Urian Oakes called him \"sprung from a most illustrious stock\" and prayed that Rawson might \"in learning, holiness and excellence of character, resemble both Wilson and Grindal.\""},{"number":2,"category":"religion","header":"Mastered Algonquian; preached and translated for natives","body":"He learned the Algonquian language and preached sermons in it to local Nipmuc parishioners — translating Thomas Shepard's Sincere Convert, John Cotton's Spiritual Milk, and a Confession of Faith. Cotton Mather called him 'a Master that had scarce an Equal' in the language."},{"number":3,"category":"religion","header":"Ordered to sail with the Canada invasion","body":"In July 1692 the General Court ordered four ministers, Rawson among them, to accompany the forces in the expedition against Canada, “to carry on the worshipping of God.” Whether he sailed with Sir William Phipps is 